    "reasoning": "The problem describes a Moore machine with two states, A and B, and specific transitions based on input values. The states are defined by the output value (A=0, B=1). From the state transition diagram:\n1. When in state B (output=1) and input=0, transition to state A (output=0).\n2. When in state B (output=1) and input=1, stay in state B (output=1).\n3. When in state A (output=0) and input=0, transition to state B (output=1).\n4. When in state A (output=0) and input=1, stay in state A (output=0).\n\nTo implement this, we need:\n- A state register to hold current state (0 or 1)\n- Combinational logic to determine next state based on current state and input\n- Combinational logic to determine output based on current state\n- Asynchronous reset to initialize the machine to state B (output=1)\n\nWe'll use a localparam for states to make the code readable. The reset is asynchronous, so we check for areset being high in the always block and set the state accordingly. Since this is a Moore machine, the output depends only on the current state.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input areset,\n    input in,\n    output out\n);\n\n    localparam STATE_A = 1'b0;\n    localparam STATE_B = 1'b1;\n\n    logic state;\n    logic state_next;\n\n    // Sequential logic\n    always @(posedge clk or posedge areset) begin\n        if (areset)\n            state <= STATE_B;\n        else\n            state <= state_next;\n    end\n\n    // Next state combinational logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        case (state)\n            STATE_B: state_next = in ? STATE_B : STATE_A;\n            STATE_A: state_next = in ? STATE_A : STATE_B;\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // Output combinational logic\n    always @(*) begin\n        out = state;\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
